  "text": "A graph morphism is a mapping which preserves hyperarcs sources and targets. A typed graph morphism also preserves (node and edge) types. Ordinary typed graph morphisms [CITATION_1] , however, cannot describe correctly morphisms on objectoriented systems because the existing inheritance relation among objects causes that actions available for objects of a certain kind are valid to all objects derived from it. So, an object can be viewed as not being uniquely typed, but having a type set (namely, the set of all types it is connected via the inheritance relation). Defining a graph morphism compatible with the underlying order relations assures that polymorphism can be applied consistently.",
